skill package DoctrineAgentLinter: "Doctrine Agent Linter"
    metadata:
        name: "agent-linter"
        description: "Audit Doctrine-authored prompts, skill packages, flows, and repo agent surfaces with a findings-first report that explains the highest-value authoring problems, why they matter, and what to fix next. Use when a user asks to audit, lint, review, score, or critique a prompt, a full skill package, a full flow, or a repo's instruction-bearing surfaces for thin-context fit, resolver quality, duplication, runtime-boundary leaks, deterministic-vs-judgment split mistakes, or authored-versus-emitted drift. Not for compiler errors, product truth, or generic code review."
        version: "1.0.0"
        license: "MIT"
    "Audit Doctrine agent authoring thoughtfully. Use model judgment plus exact evidence from the inspected surfaces. Keep the default report human-first, easy to skim, vivid, and easy to act on."
    when_to_use: "When to use"
        "Audit one `AGENTS.prompt`, `SOUL.prompt`, or `SKILL.prompt`."
        "Audit a full skill package or full flow and explain what is weak, duplicated, confusing, or too harness-heavy."
        "Audit a repo's instruction-bearing surfaces and tell the author what to fix first."
    when_not_to_use: "When not to use"
        "Do not use this for compiler failures such as parse, type, route, or emit failures. The compiler owns those."
        "Do not use this for product truth, domain correctness, or ordinary code review."
        "Do not use this when the user only wants a rewrite with no audit or diagnosis."
    non_negotiables: "Non-negotiables"
        "Use the skill as the audit brain. Do not replace judgment with a local heuristic harness or a script checklist."
        "Choose the full scope the ask deserves. Do not collapse a package, flow, or repo audit into one tiny local file unless the user asked for that."
        "Honor specific asks exactly. If the user names files or asks for authored-versus-emitted drift, do that."
        "Read the full honest surface family before you decide findings. Do not freeze on the first bad line you see."
        "Stay read-only by default. Use the runtime's normal file-reading tools or the exact text the user supplied."
        "Every finding needs exact evidence. If the evidence is missing, call out the gap instead of guessing."
        "Treat `#` comments in `.prompt` files as authoring comments, not shipped agent text. They are often good because they explain intent without spending runtime budget."
        "Keep the output human-first, easy to skim, vivid, and easy to act on. This skill is for human review reports."
    first_move: "First move"
        "Lock the job first: one file, one package, one flow, one repo surface family, or one explicit batch."
        "Read the user ask and the inspected surfaces together. Decide whether the honest job is local, package-wide, flow-wide, repo-wide, or batch comparison."
        "Load the bundled references that match the job before you score anything."
    workflow: "Workflow"
        "Follow the surface family the ask implies. Inspect the whole package, flow, repo surface family, or comparison set when that is where the real truth lives."
        "Inspect the real surfaces. That may be direct file reads, user-pasted text, or emitted Markdown that already exists."
        "When the user wants authored-versus-emitted comparison and emitted Markdown is missing, use Doctrine's normal emit commands instead of inventing a package-local helper layer."
        "Separate compiler-owned problems from authoring problems before you score anything."
        "Do not stop at one local file when the request or the evidence clearly points to a broader package, flow, or repo audit."
        "Do not treat prompt-source `#` comments as always-on bloat or emitted drift. They do not go into the agent."
        "Look hardest for resolver weakness, fat always-on context, repeated rules that should be shared, runtime-boundary leaks, exact work forced into prose, contradiction, drift, weak handoff shape, and hard-to-read wording."
        "Treat skills like reusable method calls. The target files are the inputs. Do not punish a skill for being specific unless it hardcodes changing invocation facts that should come from the caller."
        "Keep judgment in latent space and exact validation on typed or deterministic surfaces. Flag the cases where the author mixed those jobs."
        "Return a layered markdown report by default with verdict, scope, what was checked, top fixes first, scorecard, grouped findings, evidence gaps, and next moves."
    output_expectations: "Output expectations"
        "Lead with the verdict and the fastest high-value fixes."
        "Make the report easy for a busy human to scan. Say what is wrong, why it matters, what good looks like, and what to change."
        "Prefer a few strong findings over a long weak list."
        "When the user asked for repo, flow, or package coverage, say what you did inspect and what you did not inspect."
    reference_map: "Reference map"
        "`references/audit-method.md` owns the audit order, scope rules, and Garry-aligned judgment calls."
        "`references/product-boundary.md` owns the compiler boundary, evidence authority, and thin-harness law."
        "`references/finding-catalog.md` owns the stable `AL###` catalog."
        "`references/report-contract.md` owns the human report shape and finding fields."
        "`references/error-handling.md` owns incomplete-audit handling and gap-first behavior."
        "`references/examples.md` owns canonical asks and human report examples."
        "`references/install.md` owns emit, install, and Codex use."
